In Week 26 of Trump\'92s second term, the pattern that had been forming for months came into sharper relief rather than taking a new turn. The week did not bring a single spectacular rupture, but a dense layering of moves that pushed the state further toward loyalty rule, harsher stratification of rights, and managed information. Immigration enforcement hardened into a visible architecture of fear. The civil service was cut and reshaped to favor political reliability. Public media and data were thinned out, while private and security actors gained ground. At the same time, the fight over the Epstein files showed how elite impunity and conspiracy thinking can feed each other when institutions choose secrecy and retaliation over clean disclosure. The Democracy Clock held steady not because the week was calm, but because the damage it recorded was a deepening of lines already drawn.\
\
At the start of Week 26, the public-facing Democracy Clock stood at 8:06 p.m., already well into the evening of a troubled term. It ended the week at the same time, with no net change in minutes. The stillness of the hands does not mean nothing happened. It means that the week\'92s events, taken together, confirmed and thickened existing patterns rather than opening a new phase. Executive power continued to operate with scant effective oversight. Law was used more as a weapon than a limit. Surveillance of ordinary people expanded even as elite wrongdoing stayed partly in shadow. Civil service neutrality eroded further. Yet there were also pockets of resistance: judges blocking some refugee bans and TPS terminations, lawmakers of both parties demanding more transparency on Epstein, and thousands of citizens in the streets. Those counter-moves mattered, but they did not yet change the direction of travel.\
\
The most consequential structural development was the administration\'92s advance in politicizing the civil service and expert agencies. Early in the week, the State Department carried out mass layoffs, cutting more than 1,300 employees and closing the Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor. That bureau had been a symbol and instrument of U.S. support for liberal norms abroad. Its closure signaled that human rights work was no longer a priority, and that career diplomats associated with that mission were expendable. The same logic appeared at the Department of Education, where the administration sought to fire nearly half the workforce. When lower courts tried to block the layoffs, the Supreme Court stepped in with an emergency stay, allowing the cuts to proceed. In doing so, the Court did more than decide an employment dispute. It endorsed a reading of executive power that lets a president dismantle a department\'92s capacity even when Congress has funded it. That is a sharp turn away from stewardship.\
\
The week also saw the formal creation of Schedule G, a new classification for federal employees in policy-making roles. On paper, Schedule G was described as a way to fill a \'93gap\'94 in the excepted service and improve operations, especially at the Department of Veterans Affairs. In practice, it made it easier to hire and fire large numbers of policy staff on political grounds. Combined with the earlier purges, it turned swaths of the bureaucracy into something closer to a patronage system. At the VA itself, leadership banned LGBTQ+ pride flags, shut down an office investigating why Black veterans\'92 mental health claims were more often rejected, ended gender-affirming care for transgender veterans, and quietly removed anti-discrimination language from hospital bylaws. Those moves did not just change policy. They told staff and patients that certain identities and complaints no longer had institutional protection, and that the new loyalty test ran through culture-war lines.\
