The Justice Department was pulled into the same pattern. Attorney General Pam Bondi fired the department\'92s top ethics adviser, Joseph Tirrell, without explanation, and more than twenty other DOJ employees were also pushed out. Nearly two-thirds of the lawyers in the unit charged with defending Trump administration policies resigned, many saying they did not want to help dismantle constitutional structures. At the same time, the administration bypassed a judicial panel that had rejected John Sarcone III for an interim U.S. attorney post by appointing him instead as a \'93special attorney to the attorney general\'94 with the same powers and no time limit. The Senate Judiciary Committee advanced Emil Bove\'92s nomination to a federal appeals court despite a whistleblower\'92s allegation that he had urged ignoring court orders, and despite a Democratic walkout. Taken together, these moves showed how prosecutorial and judicial roles were being filled and emptied on the basis of loyalty and usefulness rather than neutral competence. The guardrails inside law enforcement and the courts grew thinner.\
