The second major development was the consolidation of a harsh, surveillance-heavy immigration regime that treated non-citizens\'97and sometimes citizens\'97as people with fewer rights. The administration moved to end bond hearings for immigrants who entered without legal status, shifting release decisions from judges to DHS officials and making detention the default. ICE Director Todd Lyons issued a memo allowing deportations to third countries with as little as six hours\'92 notice, often without firm assurances against persecution or torture. A separate policy change made undocumented immigrants ineligible for bond hearings while they challenged deportation, affecting millions. These were not emergency measures tied to a specific crisis. They were rules designed to normalize a rights-poor zone around immigration enforcement.\
