On the ground, those rules were enforced with visible force. ICE raids at licensed cannabis farms in California used tear gas and less-lethal ammunition, injuring workers and protesters. A 57-year-old farm worker, Jaime Alan\'eds, died after falling from a greenhouse roof while trying to hide. Hundreds were arrested, including a disabled veteran and a university professor who was later charged with assaulting an officer. In Los Angeles, ICE used Terminal Island as a staging ground for workplace raids that swept up nearly 2,800 people in two weeks, a place whose history of Japanese American incarceration gave the images a deeper resonance. In Oregon, agents broke a car window and arrested Mahdi Khanbabazadeh, an Iranian father, outside his child\'92s preschool, the first confirmed immigration arrest at a school in that state after the administration loosened rules on \'93sensitive locations.\'94 An Irish tourist who overstayed his visa by three days due to a medical issue was held for about 100 days in various detention facilities, including a federal prison, before being deported and banned for ten years. These were not isolated excesses. They were the visible edge of a system that treated some lives as disposable.\
