Behind these scenes, the data infrastructure of enforcement thickened. ProPublica reported that the IRS was developing a system to share confidential tax data, including home addresses, with ICE for deportation targeting, despite earlier legal objections from the agency\'92s own counsel. The administration also reached an agreement to give ICE access to Medicaid data on roughly 79 million recipients, including addresses and Social Security numbers, under the stated aim of preventing fraud. Career civil servants had warned that such sharing might violate statutes and chill people from seeking care. The One Big Beautiful Bill Act, signed earlier in the month, poured more than $6 billion into border surveillance technology: biometric towers, license plate readers, phone hacking tools, and expanded social media monitoring. These contracts enriched firms like Palantir and Anduril and embedded private actors in the core of state coercive power. The result was a system in which masked ICE agents, sometimes without clear identification, could move through communities backed by vast data flows from health and tax systems that had not been built for this purpose. Surveillance of ordinary people grew denser even as elite crimes stayed opaque.\
