Courts and civil society did not stand entirely aside. A federal judge in Los Angeles temporarily blocked ICE raids that relied on racial profiling, insisting on reasonable suspicion standards. Another court granted a temporary restraining order to keep an Ohio imam, Ayman Soliman, from being transferred out of state before his bond hearing. A federal appeals court paused the administration\'92s attempt to end Temporary Protected Status for nearly 12,000 Afghans, and a separate judge blocked the use of a presidential proclamation to bar 80 vetted refugees from entering the country. A class-action suit was filed in Washington, D.C., challenging courthouse arrests of immigrants and their advocates as violations of due process and the Fifth Amendment. Representative Pramila Jayapal announced plans for legislation to bar ICE from detaining and deporting U.S. citizens, after reports that citizens had been swept up in raids. These actions showed that parts of the judiciary and legislature were still willing to contest the new enforcement architecture. But they were reactive and piecemeal, while the administration\'92s program was broad and coordinated.\
