The pattern extended into politics. Texas Attorney General Ken Paxton threatened to arrest Democratic legislators who boycotted a special session on redistricting, a tactic long used by both parties to deny quorums. President Trump openly called for a \'93simple redraw\'94 of the Texas congressional map to gain five more Republican seats and suggested similar moves in other states. Texas Republicans moved ahead with plans for mid-decade redistricting that would weaken the influence of the state\'92s growing nonwhite population. In Florida, the state supreme court upheld a congressional map that dismantled a Black-influence district and split it into four majority-white districts, rejecting challenges under the state\'92s Fair Districts Amendment. In North Carolina, the Republican-controlled elections board voted to require additional ID data from voters, a change that could purge nearly 100,000 people from the rolls or force them into provisional ballots that might not be counted. Each of these steps was justified in the language of legality and integrity. Taken together, they entrenched a system in which some voters\'92 voices counted less by design.\
