The fourth major development was the coordinated weakening of public goods in information and foreign engagement, and the parallel strengthening of crony networks. Congress and the administration moved in tandem to cut $9 billion in previously approved spending, including $1.1 billion for the Corporation for Public Broadcasting and about $8 billion for foreign aid. A rescissions package, first advanced by the White House and then passed by both chambers, retroactively blessed unilateral executive clawbacks and reoriented federal priorities away from public broadcasting and international assistance. A separate bill in the Senate sought to cut $9 billion from public broadcasting and foreign aid, preserving only $400 million for the PEPFAR HIV/AIDS program after pushback. The U.S. Agency for Global Media was largely dismantled, ending many U.S.-backed international broadcasting efforts. These moves did not silence all independent voices, but they thinned out the noncommercial, public-facing parts of the information system and left more space for private and partisan outlets. Independent media was starved while state-aligned and market-aligned outlets thrived.\
