Threaded through all of this was the Epstein files saga, which became a kind of mirror for the system\'92s handling of elite wrongdoing and public distrust. The DOJ and FBI issued a memo concluding that Epstein had died by suicide and that no incriminating client list existed, and they announced that no further disclosures would be made. That decision angered not only Trump\'92s critics but also parts of his base, who had long been promised a reckoning with \'93elites.\'94 MAGA influencers called for Bondi\'92s firing. Elon Musk used his platform to ask why the files had not been released. Dan Bongino, now deputy FBI director, was drawn into the controversy. House Democrats introduced resolutions and amendments to force release of the files, only to see them blocked in the Rules Committee. House Republicans twice voted down Democratic attempts to mandate disclosure within 30 days, even as Speaker Mike Johnson publicly urged the DOJ to release more documents and explain itself. Senator Dick Durbin wrote to DOJ and FBI seeking details on the assignment of 1,000 agents to the case. Senator Ron Wyden pressed for access to bank reports on Epstein\'92s financial network. Pressure came from many directions.\
