Civil society also asserted itself in more direct political ways. Over 1,500 protests took place across the country under the banner \'93Good Trouble Lives On,\'94 honoring the legacy of John Lewis and calling for voting rights, justice, and dignity. The grassroots group Indivisible ran online trainings to prepare people for organizing and protest. Polling showed that 79 percent of American adults viewed immigration as beneficial and 85 percent supported pathways to citizenship for undocumented people brought as children, a stark contrast with the administration\'92s enforcement agenda. These signals did not yet translate into policy change, but they showed that public opinion and civic energy were not fully aligned with the direction of federal power. The moral floor was sagging, but it had not collapsed.\
