Looking ahead from Week 26, several processes were already in motion that would shape the next chapters. The Texas special session on redistricting, called under Trump\'92s urging and backed by threats from the state attorney general, was set to test how far a state could go in mid-decade map-drawing and how courts would respond. California\'92s governor had floated ways to counter that move, raising the prospect of a broader redistricting arms race. The rescissions package cutting public broadcasting and foreign aid had cleared both chambers and awaited the president\'92s signature, which would lock in a new spending baseline. The Supreme Court\'92s stay on Education Department layoffs had already taken effect, but the underlying case about executive power over the civil service remained live. Lawsuits challenging courthouse arrests, FEMA grant cuts, and the \'93Alligator Alcatraz\'94 detention facility were in early stages, with potential to clarify or narrow the administration\'92s reach. And the partial unsealing of Epstein grand jury materials, if carried through, would test whether limited transparency could restore any trust in institutions that had chosen secrecy and retaliation for so long.\
